To click a button of type "submit" after filling in the inputs, we can simply modify the provided script to find the button and trigger a click event on it. Here's the updated script:

```javascript
(function() {
    // Function to generate random email
    function generateRandomEmail() {
        var prefix = "user";
        var suffix = "@gmail.com";
        var randomNumber = Math.floor(Math.random() * 1000000); // Adjusted for a smaller number
        return prefix + randomNumber + suffix;
    }

    // Function to set the value of an input element
    function setInputValue(inputId, value) {
        var inputElement = document.querySelector(`#${inputId}`);
        if (inputElement) {
            inputElement.value = value;
            // Dispatch input event to simulate user typing
            inputElement.dispatchEvent(new Event('input', { bubbles: true }));
            // Dispatch change event in case it's needed
            inputElement.dispatchEvent(new Event('change', { bubbles: true }));
        } else {
            console.error(`Element with ID ${inputId} not found.`);
        }
    }

    // Function to click the submit button
    function clickSubmitButton() {
        // Find the submit button on the page
        var submitButton = document.querySelector('button[type="submit"]');
        if (submitButton) {
            // Click the submit button
            submitButton.click();
        } else {
            console.error('Submit button not found.');
        }
    }

    // Assign a randomly generated email to mat-input-4
    setInputValue('mat-input-4', generateRandomEmail());

    // Assign the preset password to mat-input-5
    const presetPassword = "Aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa1";
    setInputValue('mat-input-5', presetPassword);

    // After a short delay to ensure all input values are set, click the submit button
    setTimeout(clickSubmitButton, 100);
})();
```

This script now includes a function `clickSubmitButton()` that looks for the `<button>` with the `type="submit"` and simulates a mouse click on it. After setting the values for the email and password inputs, the `setTimeout` function is used to delay the button click slightly, ensuring that the input events have time to propagate and any form validation JavaScript has time to update the UI accordingly.

Remember to test this script on a development environment or with permission on the target website, as automating interactions could be against the site's policies. Additionally, if the form has more complex validation or event handling, this simple approach might not suffice, and additional steps may be required to ensure the form is submitted correctly.

Yes, you can make this script self-repeating by refreshing the page and then waiting for it to load again before running the script one more time. However, you'll need to use a mechanism to signal to the script that it should run again after the page loads.

Here's a simple way to achieve this using `localStorage` to set a flag that indicates the script should run again. This example uses a self-invoking function to check the flag and run the script if necessary:

```javascript
(function() {
    // Function to generate random email
    function generateRandomEmail() {
        var prefix = "randomUser";
        var suffix = "@gmail.com";
        var randomNumber = Math.floor(Math.random() * 1000000);  // Adjusted for a smaller number
        return prefix + randomNumber + suffix;
    }

    // Function to set the value of an input element
    function setInputValue(inputId, value) {
        var inputElement = document.querySelector(`#${inputId}`);
        if (inputElement) {
            inputElement.value = value;
            inputElement.dispatchEvent(new Event('input', { bubbles: true }));
            inputElement.dispatchEvent(new Event('change', { bubbles: true }));
        } else {
            console.error(`Element with ID ${inputId} not found.`);
        }
    }

    // Function to click the submit button
    function clickSubmitButton() {
        var submitButton = document.querySelector('button[type="submit"]');
        if (submitButton) {
            submitButton.click();
        } else {
            console.error('Submit button not found.');
        }
    }

    // Check if we need to run the script again
    if (localStorage.getItem('shouldFillForm') === 'true') {
        // If so, run the script
        setInputValue('mat-input-4', generateRandomEmail());
        setInputValue('mat-input-5', "Aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa1");

        // Give a slight delay to ensure inputs are filled
        setTimeout(clickSubmitButton, 100);

        // Set the flag to false after clicking the submit button
        localStorage.setItem('shouldFillForm', 'false');

        // Refresh the page to run the script again after some delay to allow form submission
        setTimeout(function() {
            location.reload();
        }, 2000);  // Adjust this time as needed to allow form processing
    }
})();

// Set the flag to true to run on the first time
localStorage.setItem('shouldFillForm', 'true');
// Reload the page to start the process
location.reload();
```

To use the repeating script, just paste it into your browser's console and run it. It will fill in the form, submit it, and then reload the page and repeat the process.

Keep in mind:

1. Auto-refreshing and submitting forms can look suspicious to website security and can be considered an abuse of service. Always have permission from the site owner before running such scripts.
2. If the form submission navigates to a different page or the session changes, this approach might not work correctly.
3. You may need to manually stop this script by clearing the localStorage flag (`localStorage.setItem('shouldFillForm', 'false');`) or closing the tab/browser.

